Specifies how many memcached read operations (get) to perform before doing a COMMIT to start a new transaction
Specifies how many memcached write operations, such as add, set, or incr, to perform before doing a COMMIT to start a new transaction
Specifies how often to auto-commit idle connections that use the InnoDB memcached interface.
Disables the use of row locks when using the InnoDB memcached interface.
Locks the table used by the InnoDB memcached plugin, so that it cannot be dropped or altered by DDL through the SQL interface.
Lets you control the transaction isolation level on queries processed by the memcached interface.
The binding protocol to use which can be either auto, ascii, or binary. The default is auto which means the server automatically negotiates the protocol with the client.
The backlog queue configures how many network connections can be waiting to be processed by memcached
Disable the use of compare and swap (CAS) which reduces the per-item size by 8 bytes.
Minimum chunk size in bytes to allocate for the smallest item's key, value, and flags. The default is 48 and you can get a significant memory efficiency gain with a lower value.
Chunk size growth factor that controls the size of each successive chunk with each chunk growing times this amount larger than the previous chunk.
If enabled when there is no more memory to store items, memcached will return an error rather than evicting items.
Maximum number of concurrent connections. Setting this value to anything less than 10 prevents MySQL from starting.
Verbose level for memcached.
